makeMult

public Expr makeMult()
This function is needed to handle a difficult parsing ambiguity.

"some X", "one X", and "lone X" can be either formulas, or multiplicity constraints.

So we let the parser generate the former by default. And whenever we construct a "VarDecl(a,b)" object, or a "ExprBinary.Op.IN(a,b)" object, we call this method on b to convert it into a multiplicity constraint.

This is safe, because in both cases, a formula would be illegal. So the first form is always wrong.

And this is sufficient, because those are the only 2 places where a mulitplicity constraint is allowed to appear.
